Question about HW3

Henrik Eckermann

Problem

While working on HW 3 I was somewhat confused by the order of the slopes and intercepts by xyplot. For personal interest I wanted to recreate the plot with ggplot2. I thought that xyplot orders the panels based on the intercept and slopes of a multilevel model. However, it became clear that this is not the case. So, to save you confusion in the future and investing half your Sunday on that I put it on BB. To see what I mean I show it with the example that is familiar to all of us now using the task from the HW3:

#center variable
df$c_trial <- df$num_trial - mean(df$num_trial)
#fit model
fit <- lmer(distance ~ gender * c_trial + (1 + c_trial|pid) , data=df)

So, here the xyplot with descending order of intercepts (if you read from left to right, bottom to top). I used c_trial because I used c_trial also for the model. You can also use num_trial but then you also have to use num_trial in the model to show that what xyplot is using since the intercepts change with centering (and beware that the intercept is now in the middle of the plot and not left).

xyplot(distance ~ c_trial | pid, data=df, type=c('g', 'p', 'r'), index.cond =  function(x,y) -coef(lm(y ~ x))[1])

In the following, I fit a linear regression for each individual using also c_trial. I further extract the MLM coefficients including the deviations from the fixed parameters, store everything in a dataframe and then we can order that dataframe by the parameter of interest to check which order is similar to the order xyplot uses:

#Store coefs in dataframe
cf <- coef(fit)$pid %>% rownames_to_column('pid')
#change colnames of dataframe
names(cf) <- c('pid', 'mlm_intercepts', 'gender_coef', 'mlm_slopes', 'interaction')
#Same for deviations from fixed effects: 
cf2 <- ranef(fit)$pid %>% rownames_to_column('pid')
names(cf2) <- c('pid', 'mlm_intercepts_dev', 'mlm_slopes_dev')
#Perform linear regression for each individual:
fitted_models = df %>% group_by(pid) %>% do(model = lm(distance ~ c_trial, data = .))
#Create df for each estimate 
df3 <- fitted_models %>% tidy(model) %>% dlply("term", identity)
lm_coefs <- data.frame(pid=df3$`(Intercept)`$pid, lm_intercepts=df3$`(Intercept)`$estimate, lm_slopes=df3$c_trial$estimate)
#Store in one df and sort by mlm_intercept:
descending_mlm_intercepts <- dplyr::select(cf, pid, mlm_intercepts, mlm_slopes) %>%
  left_join(cf2, by='pid') %>%
  left_join(lm_coefs, by='pid') %>%
  dplyr::select(pid, mlm_intercepts, mlm_intercepts_dev, lm_intercepts, mlm_slopes, mlm_slopes_dev, lm_slopes) %>%
  arrange(desc(mlm_intercepts))
#Store in one df and sort by lm_intercept:
descending_lm_intercepts <- dplyr::select(cf, pid, mlm_intercepts, mlm_slopes) %>%
  left_join(cf2, by='pid') %>%
  left_join(lm_coefs, by='pid') %>%
  dplyr::select(pid, mlm_intercepts, mlm_intercepts_dev, lm_intercepts, mlm_slopes, mlm_slopes_dev, lm_slopes) %>%
  arrange(desc(lm_intercepts))

Compare with df

You can see in this df the order of pid how it should be if you want order by the intercepts and slopes provided by lme. I put the xyplot again here so you can directly compare and see that the order does not match:

descending_mlm_intercepts
xyplot(distance ~ c_trial | pid, data=df, type=c('g', 'p', 'r'), index.cond =  function(x,y) -coef(lm(y ~ x))[1])

And here the order xyplot uses, which are the intercepts I got by performing a single lm for each pid:

descending_lm_intercepts

In case you want to order by intercept

This plot orders by the mlm intercept. You need to read from left to right, top to bottom. You can do the same for slopes or any other parameter if you want. Again, I use c_trial so beware that the intercept is in the middel of the plot now. You can do the same if you replace c_trial with num_trial in the model fit and the code that follows after…

df <- left_join(df, cf, by='pid') %>% mutate(pid=reorder(pid, -mlm_intercepts))
##plot ordered by intercept 
ggplot(df, aes(c_trial, distance)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept=mlm_intercepts, slope=mlm_slopes),color='red') +
  facet_wrap(~pid)

descending_mlm_intercepts
